WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.000
Translator: Hélène Vernet
Reviewer: Peter van de Ven

00:00:04.970 --> 00:00:07.790
The subject of my talk tonight

00:00:07.790 --> 00:00:11.851
is about something
that is smarter than you are:

00:00:12.421 --> 00:00:14.421
artificial intelligence.

00:00:14.551 --> 00:00:18.621
In fact, a lot of people who work
in artificial intelligence believe

00:00:18.621 --> 00:00:22.421
that artificial intelligence is
a thousand times smarter than we are.

00:00:22.741 --> 00:00:24.451
It will be moving at speeds

00:00:24.451 --> 00:00:27.051
that are a hundred thousand times
as fast as we think,

00:00:27.051 --> 00:00:30.101
and it will be digesting
information and data

00:00:30.101 --> 00:00:33.091
a million times more than we can.

00:00:33.801 --> 00:00:35.351
What is artificial intelligence?

00:00:35.351 --> 00:00:39.341
There're a lot of confused ideas
about this outside in the world,

00:00:39.951 --> 00:00:42.981
but the answer is very simple;
it's one sentence:

00:00:43.391 --> 00:00:47.641
artificial intelligence
is software that writes itself.

00:00:48.381 --> 00:00:52.341
It writes its own updates.
It renews itself.

00:00:53.095 --> 00:00:54.962
We normally tend to think of software

00:00:54.962 --> 00:00:57.352
as stuff that we created
and that we wrote,

00:00:57.352 --> 00:01:01.019
and the machines do what we tell
them to do, and we own it.

00:01:01.199 --> 00:01:03.799
This is not any longer true.

00:01:03.799 --> 00:01:06.609
It writes itself at speeds
that we can hardly comprehend,

00:01:06.609 --> 00:01:09.269
and people who write it know

00:01:09.269 --> 00:01:13.329
that you can't take it apart again
and figure out what it has done.

00:01:13.329 --> 00:01:16.289
It writes independently, autonomously;

00:01:16.289 --> 00:01:18.729
it develops its own way of thinking,

00:01:19.799 --> 00:01:22.229
and there are dangers
associated with that.

00:01:22.569 --> 00:01:24.879
A lot of people ask,
"When is it going to happen?

00:01:24.879 --> 00:01:29.249
When is artificial intelligence
going to be smarter than us people?"

00:01:29.859 --> 00:01:31.789
Some people say 50 years.

00:01:31.909 --> 00:01:33.759
Some say 30 years.

00:01:34.039 --> 00:01:35.949
Some say five years.

00:01:36.262 --> 00:01:40.411
I say it already has surpassed us

00:01:40.411 --> 00:01:44.241
in many areas of our society.

00:01:45.221 --> 00:01:50.340
Let's take some examples
from right here and now.

00:01:53.146 --> 00:01:55.411
The examples
that we're going to talk about

00:01:56.060 --> 00:01:57.676
are not science fiction;

00:01:57.676 --> 00:02:00.976
they're not visions or things
that are going to happen at some point.

00:02:00.976 --> 00:02:04.253
They're things that exist today,
for example in the stock markets,

00:02:04.253 --> 00:02:07.693
whether Frankfurt or Tokyo
or New York or London.

00:02:08.123 --> 00:02:12.190
The people you see down there working,
on your TV show when you're watching,

00:02:12.920 --> 00:02:15.650
they're more or less extras in a movie.

00:02:15.650 --> 00:02:18.080
They aren't doing the big moving.

00:02:18.080 --> 00:02:22.150
The big moving is being done
by high-frequency computers.

00:02:22.150 --> 00:02:27.318
They move so fast, they make,
in milliseconds, billion-dollar business.

00:02:27.631 --> 00:02:30.051
Computers have far succeeded
what we can do.

00:02:30.051 --> 00:02:32.050
In fact, I did a film once
about a company

00:02:32.050 --> 00:02:36.070
that moved five blocks closer
to the Frankfurt stock market

00:02:36.070 --> 00:02:40.216
because at the speed
of light on glass cable,

00:02:40.216 --> 00:02:42.511
they saved so much time,

00:02:42.511 --> 00:02:47.402
getting closer to the computers
at the Frankfurt Stock Exchange.

00:02:47.682 --> 00:02:50.841
That will give you an idea
of how fast they think

00:02:50.841 --> 00:02:52.801
and how helpless we,
as human beings, are.

00:02:52.801 --> 00:02:55.341
You may remember the old pictures
of the stock brokers

00:02:55.341 --> 00:02:58.831
with five telephones in each hand,
running back and forth, writing things,

00:02:58.831 --> 00:03:01.481
that was way before yesterday!

00:03:01.481 --> 00:03:05.881
Computers have taken over this very,
very important part of our society,

00:03:05.881 --> 00:03:08.751
a heart of our financial community.

00:03:08.751 --> 00:03:12.051
And no one understands exactly
how these algorithms function.

00:03:12.051 --> 00:03:13.441
They used to understand them,

00:03:13.441 --> 00:03:16.771
but they've been improved
by artificial intelligence.

00:03:16.882 --> 00:03:18.942
I don't know how many people
flew in today,

00:03:18.942 --> 00:03:20.802
but if you were sitting in an airplane,

00:03:20.802 --> 00:03:24.692
you probably had 30 different tariffs
and prices in your cabin

00:03:24.692 --> 00:03:29.442
because the pricing is all done -
the same is true of hotels -

00:03:29.442 --> 00:03:31.950
by machines that are collecting
global information,

00:03:31.950 --> 00:03:34.180
making decisions within split seconds

00:03:34.180 --> 00:03:38.370
what the price of that airplane seat
or that hotel room is going to be.

00:03:38.663 --> 00:03:41.252
And where it's most critical of all -

00:03:42.093 --> 00:03:44.023
we're talking about life and death -

00:03:44.023 --> 00:03:45.433
is in medicine.

00:03:45.583 --> 00:03:49.133
Computers are better
than we are, as human beings,

00:03:49.133 --> 00:03:51.213
in several areas already today.

00:03:51.213 --> 00:03:54.743
We're talking about here and now;
this is not science fiction.

00:03:54.743 --> 00:03:58.633
I'm speaking next week
at the Universitätsklinikum in Essen,

00:03:58.943 --> 00:04:00.802
and their radiologists,

00:04:00.808 --> 00:04:03.843
who are supposed to be
some of the best radiologists in Germany,

00:04:03.843 --> 00:04:08.654
they say that a computer
can recognize a tumor

00:04:08.654 --> 00:04:11.934
on an MRT or a CT,

00:04:11.934 --> 00:04:16.944
faster and better and more precisely
than a human being can.

00:04:17.896 --> 00:04:22.006
It's picture analysis,
and it's done very well by computers,

00:04:22.006 --> 00:04:25.436
especially in medicine
where it saves lives.

00:04:27.103 --> 00:04:30.823
Now, the robots are getting
better and better; they're looking cute.

00:04:30.823 --> 00:04:33.883
They have these big baby eyes,
a sweet way of looking at you.

00:04:33.883 --> 00:04:37.663
They can examine your facial
expression and adjust their's.

00:04:37.913 --> 00:04:41.995
But don't be fooled by robots
even when they get warm skin, perfume,

00:04:41.995 --> 00:04:45.705
and they start smelling like us
and getting really interesting.

00:04:45.705 --> 00:04:48.374
They are still machines.

00:04:48.374 --> 00:04:51.004
They have no warm blood in them.
There's no sex in them.

00:04:51.054 --> 00:04:52.754
They have no mortality.

00:04:52.824 --> 00:04:56.024
They're cold code lines,

00:04:57.031 --> 00:04:58.879
and they shouldn't be misunderstood.

00:04:58.879 --> 00:05:01.638
Now, I want you to understand

00:05:01.638 --> 00:05:04.657
what the power
of artificial intelligence is,

00:05:04.657 --> 00:05:08.677
and I have two examples:
one is surveillance cameras.

00:05:08.677 --> 00:05:12.456
Everybody knows that we're being
watched by cameras everywhere,

00:05:12.456 --> 00:05:15.286
and most people think
surveillance is a camera there,

00:05:15.286 --> 00:05:17.391
and it's me down here,
and it's watching me:

00:05:17.391 --> 00:05:19.466
one person, one camera.

00:05:19.930 --> 00:05:22.610
Well, that's because we're stupid.

00:05:22.610 --> 00:05:25.900
That's the way we comprehend
the surveillance: one camera, one person.

00:05:25.900 --> 00:05:28.510
We can't comprehend it
when it goes beyond that -

00:05:28.510 --> 00:05:30.430
(Ominous music)

